\'a0\'a0\'a0 ----- TEXT:\
\cf11 \cb12 \'a0\'a0\'a0 The paper presents an application of Event-B as a verification back-end for statecharts restricted to certain elicitation laws. My intuition is that the restriction is overly onerous but the paper does lack explicit discussion of this.\cf3 \cb1 \
\'a0\'a0\'a0\
\cf2 \cb7 \'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0As is very common with translational semantics, the difficult bit is how to communicate verification results in a way intelligible to users trained in the source (here, statecharts) notation. The authors do not address this issue.\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\cf3 \cb1 \
\cf9 \cb12 \'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0On the whole it is a fairly solid work. Personally, rather than seeing it as a way to verify statechart-driven process (something that I believe would not work in practice due to the feedback issue) I think it is, alongside with some related UML-B work, a great way to document Event-B models. Event-B is not the most legible notation and having statecharts as a way to control and document refinement seems a sound decision that can help domain experts to assess models and tick off some boxes for certification.\cf3 \cb1 \
\'a0\'a0\'a0\
\cf9 \cb12 \'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0The liveness checks solution seems a bit of an afterthought. Given controlled manner of chart eloboartion I wonder if it can be integrated within the eloboration process.\cf3 \cb1 \
\'a0\'a0\'a0\
\cf2 \cb7 \'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0There are some suprising design decisions in the semantics (e.g., using a negation of 'other' event guards) that either need an explanation or revision.\cf3 \cb1 \
\'a0\'a0\'a0\
\cf9 \cb15 \'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0The paper starts great but then the narrative gets choppier. What I persnally wished for is see more statecharts illustrations for the example. Section 7 desperately needs some improvement in the area.\cf3 \cb1 \
\'a0\'a0\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0Other comments:\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\
\cf9 \cb12 \'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0"but a rubric for finding valid refinements" - to me this oversells what Event-B offers. Certain forms of refinement are hard due to an interaction of semantics and prover capabilities. But not all "inelegant" models are bad and not all "elegant" models are good.\cf3 \cb1 \
\'a0\'a0\'a0\
\cf9 \cb12 \'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0In the background section, please include a sample of statechart model and describe the visual notation.\cf3 \cb1 \
\'a0\'a0\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\cf9 \cb12 \'a0\'a0"It is at the highest level of abstraction that proofs are presumably the easiest to\
\'a0\'a0\'a0 discharge." - but at the price (usually worth paying) of invariant preservation proofs.\cf3 \cb1 \
\'a0\'a0\'a0\
\cf9 \cb12 \'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0"preservation of safety proofs is the goal here." - this can confuse many readers. Event-B uses a syntactic form of forward simulation, a fairly common criterion for symbolic transition systems. The safety proofs business is simply entailed by the transitivity of simulation.\cf3 \cb1 \
\'a0\'a0\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\cf9 \cb12 \'a0Fig. 1 is very hard to uncipher. Prepend with definitions and types of all the identifiers. A petri net could be an apt illustration for what is happening here.\
\cf3 \cb1 \'a0\'a0\'a0\
\cf2 \cb7 \'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0"In order to preserve refinement rules, which prohibit the modication of existing variables,... " - that's a huge oversimplification.\
\'a0\cf3 \cb1 \'a0\'a0\'a0\
\cf2 \cb7 \'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0"by adding the conjunction of the negated guards of all transitions triggered by dt" - or negation of disjunction of such guards. Either way the result is outright disastrous for large models (20-50 events) as a guard is typically a conjunction of 3-10 predicates. That would introduce 20-50 hypotheses each being a disjunction made of 3-10 parts. That is way beyond what rewrite-based provers can handle.\cf3 \cb1 \
\'a0\'a0\'a0\
\cf9 \cb12 \'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0Fig.2: why only some states are elaborated? What's the half-arrow notation?\cf3 \cb1 \
\'a0\'a0\'a0\
\'a0\cf2 \cb7 \'a0\'a0\'a0"The translation of a specific SCXML" - mention the target of your translation\cf3 \cb1 \
\'a0\'a0\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\cf9 \cb12 "a basis machine and context are created" - I was expecting to find a use of the theory plugin here, any particular reason not to?\cf3 \cb1 \
\'a0\'a0\'a0\
\cf2 \cb7 \'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0"all possible combinations ... are calculated" - calculated how? It would appear you need to partition predicates into mutually satisfiable clusters - a very hard thing to do.\cf3 \cb1 \
\'a0\'a0\'a0\
\cf9 \cb12 \'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0For the statechart refinement laws can you provide a brief analysis of completeness (or how restrictive it is compared to informal elaboration)?\cf3 \cb1 \
\'a0\'a0\'a0\
\cf9 \cb12 \'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0Rule 3 requires some complicated renaming/nested binding of identifiers?\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\cf3 \cb1 \
\'a0\cf9 \cb12 \'a0\'a0\'a0Section 7 is hard to follow. I understand there are space constraints but scuh narrative detached from charts and models is really dry and hard to process. Possibly give a link to an external appendix?\cf3 \cb1 \
\'a0\'a0\'a0\
\cf2 \cb7 \'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0"It is sometimes possible to construct a model that satisfies some invariant (e.g.\
\'a0\'a0\'a0 safety) properties, but does not behave in a useful way" - that's a major understatement :). I would prefer to take a view that a model is not _adequate_ (a common term for what you describe) unless it is shown to be so.\cf3 \cb1 \
\'a0\'a0\'a0\
\'a0\cf2 \cb7 \'a0\'a0\'a0Any reason liveness proof cannot be dealt with in Rodin via proof obligations? Two of the co-authors have publications describing such techniques ;)\
\'a0\cf3 \cb1 \'a0\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0Models could be better commented.\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0Please include a paragraph detailing plugin versions necessary to properly study the project.\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0and a small readme file would be great as well to detail the setup\
